    <!-- Part 1 -->
    <section id="part1" class="card">
      <h2>Part 1 — Judaism Introduction</h2>
      <h3>What is Judaism?</h3>
      <p>Judaism is a monotheistic religion that developed among the ancient Hebrews and centers on the belief in one transcendent God who revealed laws and teachings to the people of Israel. Jewish religious life emphasizes study of sacred texts, communal worship, ethical action, and keeping religious practices such as Shabbat.</p>

      <h4>Key beliefs and practices</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>God</strong> — Jews believe in one God (monotheism), a single, transcendent Creator who revealed the Torah and entered covenantal relationship with the people of Israel.</li>
        <li><strong>Torah</strong> — The Torah (the five books of Moses) is the foundational sacred law and narrative; it is central to Jewish religious life and study.</li>
        <li><strong>Israel</strong> — Israel (both the land and the people) holds central religious, historical, and spiritual significance in Judaism; Jewish identity and many religious practices are connected to Israel and its history.</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Three sources of sacred Jewish writings (with specific examples)</h4>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Tanakh</strong> — the Hebrew Bible: three parts: Torah (e.g., Genesis, Exodus), Nevi'im (Prophets, e.g., Isaiah), Ketuvim (Writings, e.g., Psalms).</li>
        <li><strong>Talmud</strong> — rabbinic discussions and legal reasoning (Mishnah + Gemara). Example: the Mishnah tractates (e.g., Berakhot) and the Babylonian Talmud.</li>
        <li><strong>Midrash</strong> — rabbinic homiletic and interpretive writings that expand on biblical stories (examples: Midrash Rabbah on Genesis, Exodus).</li>
      </ol>

      <h4>Importance of Shabbat</h4>
      <p>Shabbat (the weekly Sabbath, from Friday evening to Saturday evening) is a central ritual rhythm in Jewish life — a day of rest, prayer, study, family meals, and communal worship. Shabbat creates sacred time and is a primary expression of Jewish identity and continuity.</p>

      <div class="images-row" aria-hidden="false">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/dc/Torah_scroll.jpg" alt="Torah scroll">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/5d/Synagogue_interior.jpg" alt="Synagogue interior">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/40/Hanukkah_menorah.jpg" alt="Menorah (Hanukkah)">
      </div>
      <small class="cite">Images: Wikimedia Commons.</small>
    </section>

    <!-- Part 2 -->
    <section id="part2" class="card">
      <h2>Part 2 — Jewish Signs and Symbols</h2>
      <p>Below are short descriptions and images for each required Jewish sign or symbol.</p>

      <ul class="symbols">
        <li><strong>Chai</strong> — Hebrew word meaning "life"; often worn as jewelry and symbolizes the value of life.</li>
        <li><strong>Kippah (Yarmulke)</strong> — small skullcap worn by many Jewish men (and some women in non-Orthodox communities) during prayer or all the time to show reverence to God.</li>
        <li><strong>Dreidel</strong> — four-sided spinning top used in a traditional Hanukkah game; each side has a Hebrew letter.</li>
        <li><strong>Menorah</strong> — a candelabrum; the nine-branched Hanukkah menorah (hanukkiah) commemorates the Hanukkah miracle; the seven-branched menorah is an ancient Temple symbol.</li>
        <li><strong>Mezuzah</strong> — a small parchment scroll with Torah verses (Deuteronomy) placed in a case and affixed to doorposts of Jewish homes.</li>
        <li><strong>Shofar</strong> — a ram's horn blown on Rosh Hashanah (and at other times) as a call to repentance and spiritual awakening.</li>
        <li><strong>Star of David (Magen David)</strong> — six-pointed star widely used as a contemporary symbol of Judaism and Jewish identity.</li>
        <li><strong>Tallit &amp; Tzitzit</strong> — prayer shawl (tallit) with ritual fringes (tzitzit) commanded in the Torah as a reminder of the commandments.</li>
        <li><strong>Tefillin</strong> — small leather boxes with Torah passages, worn during weekday morning prayers bound to the arm and forehead.</li>
        <li><strong>Torah Scroll &amp; Yad</strong> — the handwritten Torah scroll is read in synagogue; the yad (pointer) is used to follow the text without touching the parchment.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="images-row" style="margin-top:12px">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/7c/Chai_%28pendant%29.jpg" alt="Chai pendant">
