    <!-- Part 3 -->
    <section id="part3" class="card">
      <h2>Part 3 — Jewish Festivals</h2>
      <p>Each festival below is briefly described and its place in the Jewish calendar is noted (Jewish calendar months are lunar-based).</p>

      <div class="festival-grid">
        <div class="festival">
          <h4>Hanukkah</h4>
          <p>Celebrates the rededication of the Temple and the miracle of the oil. Occurs in the Jewish month of Kislev (generally November–December).</p>
          <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/40/Hanukkah_menorah.jpg" alt="Hanukkah menorah" style="width:100%;border-radius:6px;margin-top:6px">
        </div>

        <div class="festival">
          <h4>Pesach (Passover)</h4>
          <p>Commemorates the Exodus from Egypt and freedom from slavery. Takes place in Nisan (generally March–April) and begins with a Seder meal.</p>
          <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/17/Passover_seder_plate.jpg" alt="Passover Seder plate" style="width:100%;border-radius:6px;margin-top:6px">
        </div>

        <div class="festival">
          <h4>Rosh Hashanah</h4>
          <p>Jewish New Year—time of reflection and the sounding of the shofar. Occurs in Tishrei (generally September–October).</p>
          <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/47/Shofar_and_apples.jpg" alt="Shofar and apples" style="width:100%;border-radius:6px;margin-top:6px">
        </div>

        <div class="festival">
          <h4>Sukkot</h4>
          <p>A harvest festival commemorating the Israelites' time in the wilderness; participants build and eat in a sukkah (booth). Occurs in Tishrei (Sept–Oct), five days after Yom Kippur.</p>
          <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0f/Sukkah.jpg" alt="Sukkah" style="width:100%;border-radius:6px;margin-top:6px">
        </div>

        <div class="festival">
          <h4>Yom HaShoah</h4>
          <p>Holocaust Remembrance Day — a day to remember victims of the Holocaust. Observed on 27 Nisan (generally April–May).</p>
          <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/46/Candle_holocaust_memorial.jpg" alt="Candle memorial" style="width:100%;border-radius:6px;margin-top:6px">
        </div>

        <div class="festival">
          <h4>Yom Kippur</h4>
          <p>The Day of Atonement — the holiest day of the Jewish year focused on repentance, prayer, and fasting. Occurs on 10 Tishrei (Sept–Oct).</p>
          <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/6f/Yom_Kippur_Rabbi_Leading_Service.jpg" alt="Yom Kippur service" style="width:100%;border-radius:6px;margin-top:6px">
        </div>
      </div>
      <small class="cite">Festival dates follow the Jewish (Hebrew) lunar calendar; observance months shown in parentheses.</small>
    </section>

    <!-- Part 4 -->
    <section id="part4" class="card">
      <h2>Part 4 — Sacred Places</h2>
      <p>At least two sacred places in Judaism with explanations of their significance:</p>

      <div class="place" style="margin-bottom:12px">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/6f/Western_Wall_-_Jerusalem.jpg" alt="Western Wall (Wailing Wall)">
        <div>
          <h4>1. Western Wall (Kotel), Jerusalem</h4>
          <p>The Western Wall is the remaining retaining wall of the Second Temple compound and is Judaism’s most sacred site for prayer. It is a focal point for Jewish pilgrimage, prayer, and national memory because it is the closest accessible site to the ancient Temple’s Holy of Holies.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="place">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e8/Old_City_of_Jerusalem_from_the_Mount_of_Olives.jpg" alt="Temple Mount / Jerusalem">
        <div>
          <h4>2. Temple Mount / City of Jerusalem</h4>
          <p>Jerusalem as a whole — and the Temple Mount in particular — occupies central significance in Jewish history, prayer, and eschatology. Many prayers orient toward Jerusalem, and the city is central to Jewish festivals and identity.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <small class="cite">Images: Wikimedia Commons.</small>
    </section>

