    <!-- Part 6 -->
    <section id="part6" class="card">
      <h2>Part 6 — Similarities and Differences with Christianity</h2>
      <p>Below are two similarities and two differences. Each item is given its own paragraph and includes a direct quotation (from public sources) with an in-text citation.</p>

      <h4>Similarity 1 — Monotheism (belief in one God)</h4>
      <p>Both Judaism and Christianity are monotheistic traditions that trace their roots to the Hebrew Scriptures and the belief in one God who created the world and revealed moral law. A relevant quotation: <span class="quote">“Judaism is a monotheistic religion developed among the ancient Hebrews. It is characterized by a belief in one transcendent God who revealed himself to Abraham, Moses, and the Hebrew prophets.”</span>
      <small class="cite">Source: Encyclopaedia Britannica — "Judaism." </small>
      </p>

      <h4>Similarity 2 — Shared Scriptures (Hebrew Bible / Old Testament)</h4>
      <p>Both religions revere the Hebrew Bible (often called the Old Testament in Christianity) as sacred scripture; many narratives, laws, and prophets are common to both faiths. Quotation: <span class="quote">“Faith in Jesus Christ is related in the closest way to faith in the kingdom of God... Christian eschatological expectations were joined with messianic promises, which underwent a decisive transformation and differentiation in late Judaism.”</span>
      <small class="cite">Source: Encyclopaedia Britannica — "Christianity / Messianic views."</small>
      </p>

      <h4>Difference 1 — The nature of the Messiah / Savior</h4>
      <p>A major theological difference is that Christianity identifies Jesus as the Messiah and divine (Son of God), while Judaism continues to await a future human Messiah and does not accept Jesus as divine. Quotation: <span class="quote">“Christians commonly refer to Jesus of Nazareth as either the 'Christ' or the 'Messiah', believing that some messianic prophecies were fulfilled in the mission, death, and resurrection of Jesus... the majority of historical and mainline Christian theologies consider Jesus to be the Son of God.”</span>
      <small class="cite">Source: Encyclopaedia Britannica — "Messiah (religion)."</small>
      </p>

      <h4>Difference 2 — Role and observance of the Sabbath and law</h4>
      <p>Judaism treats the Sabbath (Shabbat) as a weekly sacred institution central to Jewish communal and family life, with specific laws and rituals; Christian observance of a weekly rest day varies widely and is often centered on Sunday worship rather than full Jewish Shabbat rituals. Quotation: <span class="quote">“The Shabbat... begins at sunset... Shabbat candles are lit and a blessing is recited no later than eighteen minutes before sunset... This ritual... officially marks the beginning of the Shabbat.”</span>
      <small class="cite">Source: Jewish Virtual Library — "What is Shabbat."</small>
      </p>
    </section>

